Midgaard's charter theorists study the Heraldic Ten as an example of collective-responsibility
governance that was deliberately designed to resist accountability rather than to enable it.
The Ten's staged concurrence requirement—each member signing escalation decisions as one of
ten—is structurally analogous to the Continuity faction's practice of routing sensitive decisions
through multi-signature administrative committees: the decision is made, the signatures are
obtained, but the deliberation that produced the decision is not recorded. When accountability
is sought, each signatory points to the collective. The Reckoning faction cites the Ten's model
specifically when arguing that Midgaard's multi-signature sealed warrant process during the
Violet Compact era was designed with the same accountability-evasion function in mind. The
parallel is not coincidental: Kel'Shadra institutional practices, including the Heraldic Ten
model, informed Midgaard's administrative architecture during the Violet Compact period.

